"Everything we've shown so far — the foundation, the cycle, the rules — exists to produce one thing: the evidence inventory. From the navigation, we open Active Evidences. Each row is one piece of audit-time proof the organization tracks — one control, one application, anchored to one cycle. You'll notice the same control appearing many times. That's by design: a single control like Configuration and Change Control applies to many applications, and each application needs its own evidence record. One row per accountability point — one control, one application, one owner. Many rows show Gap. Gap isn't a problem; it's an honest state. Every compliance program has gaps; the platform's job is to make them visible, named, and trackable. We click into one record. This is what makes the data model novel: an evidence record captures the relationship between a control and an application at a specific moment in time. The platform takes a snapshot — the control description, the application attributes, the cycle context — and pins them to this record permanently. Even if the source records change later, the audit trail remembers what they were at the moment of collection. Three years from now, an auditor pulls this cycle's evidence and sees exactly what the control, the application, and the decision looked like at that moment."
